Bill DeWitt III ’90, president of the St. Louis @Cardinals, recalls the team’s historic come-from-behind victory in Game 6 of the 2011 World Series.

Hear the full conversation with his father, Bill DeWitt Jr. ’63, the team’s chairman and CEO, and President Peter Salovey — about leadership lessons from the pandemic, @YaleAthletics, and the rise of sabermetrics — all in the latest Yale Talk podcast: president.yale.edu/yale-talk

#Yale #YaleAlumni #ThisIsYale

Class Day speaker and double-EGOT composer Bobby Lopez ’97 created “The Beacon” specifically for the Harkness Tower carillon. 

Lopez is the songwriter behind “Frozen,” “Coco,” “Avenue Q,” and “Book of Mormon.”

The Beacon was played during today’s Class Day ceremony by graduate Paul Stelben ’21, the only carillonneur in Yale’s history to be certified by the Guild of Carillonneurs in North America, which he achieved as a sophomore.

Experience all the Class Day traditions and festivities, including more musical performances, at yale2021.yale.edu

Yale Class Day begins now! Watch the full ceremony at: yale2021.yale.edu/class-day

Yale Glee Club came together in person for the first time in over a year to lend their voices to several favorite pieces from the group’s repertoire, including “Alleluia,” “Bright College Years,” and this piece — “Raise Your Voices Here” by @yalegleeclub Director Jeffrey Douma. 

The ceremony will include these performances, reflections from the graduating class, an address by songwriter Robert Lopez ’97, and many other traditions dating back to Class Day’s origins in the 19th century.

#OTD in 1860: the Yale Corporation voted to establish the degree of Doctor of Philosophy. At commencement 1861, Yale awarded 3 PhDs — the first in the United States.

In 1892, Yale established the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences (@yalegsas) to house the doctoral programs.

In 1876, Edward Alexander Bouchet (Yale College Class of 1874) became the first African American to earn a PhD in the U.S., with the 6th doctorate ever awarded in physics in the U.S.

In 1892, women were admitted as graduate students in full standing, and in 1894, 7 women became the first to earn a Yale PhD.

node.text:
“Yale-o-nauts” Tyler Krebs ’21, Paul Meuser ’22, and Rishab Jain ’21 took a zero-gravity parabolic research flight to test out their designs as a capstone to their spring semester @yalearchitecture class.

The graduate students were challenged to imagine architectural “artifacts” from a Space Age in which humans populate the moon, Mars, and orbiting outposts. They conceived, designed, and fabricated objects — such as a storage container, flower vase, and specialized camera — that might become part of the fabric of off-planet life in the not-too-distant future. 

The 90-minute flight performed 20 parabolas — upward and downward arcs that produce microgravity and zero-gravity conditions — interspersed with periods of level flight. 

The researchers laid flat on the cabin floor and absorbed the g-forces as the aircraft climbed to the parabola’s apex, then rose into the air as it dove. The first several parabolas simulated lunar and Martian gravity.

Tyler: “It was crazy. If you did a pushup, you’d almost throw yourself into the ceiling. The slightest jump made you hover.”

Paul: “You start floating and you can never get 100% control of your body. It was hard to keep my body from spinning or tilting.”

Performing experiments amid the visceral excitement of experiencing of micro- and-zero gravity for the first time was challenging.

Paul: “After the first several parabolas, our carefully laid plans went out the window.”

But they persisted and completed the tests even when they weren’t in complete control of their movements.

Tyler: “The experience of your body in zero gravity is amazing, but watching an everyday object behaving differently than you expected was fascinating.” 

Seeing their classmates floating midair is an image they won't soon forget. 

The class was taught by Yale Center for Collaborative Arts and Media (@yaleccam) director Dana Karwas and alumna Ariel Ekblaw ’14, who studied physics, mathematics, and philosophy at Yale, and then earned a doctorate in space architecture from MIT. 

The course is a collaboration with MIT's Media Lab Space Exploration Initiative, and the flight included a @mitpics team. 

📷: Steve Boxall, ZERO-G #yale

node.text:
Over the last 16 months, as COVID-19 dramatically upended routine life and now gradually subsides in many places, including Connecticut, few spaces on the Yale campus saw as much transformation as the Lanman Center in Payne Whitney Gymnasium.

Early in the pandemic, Lanman — normally a place for basketball, volleyball, and jogging — was converted into a field hospital, replete with hand-washing areas, nursing stations, and metal-framed rooms to accommodate contaminated clothing and high-risk procedures. 

Months later it became Yale’s primary vaccination center, offering many people not only protection from disease but also a deep sense of relief.

And now, more than a year since the last basketball dropped through a hoop there, the Lanman Center is coming full circle: Work crews have spent weeks restoring the center to its former glory as vaccination operations are transferred to the Rose Center on Ashmun Street.

We're taking a look back at how an unforgettable year played out at Lanman, which served as an instrument for the tireless work and devotion of the healthcare providers who have served our community.

📷: Andrew Hurley and Dan Renzetti  #yale

Present and future students at Yale’s drama school will no longer pay tuition, thanks to a landmark $150 million gift from entertainment executive and philanthropist David Geffen.

The donation — the largest on record in the history of American theater — makes the school the only institution of its kind to eliminate tuition for all degree and certificate students, removing financial barriers to access.

In recognition of the gift, Yale School of Drama is now the David Geffen School of Drama at Yale University (@GeffenYale).

The Geffen School of Drama will eliminate tuition for all degree and certificate students, starting with those enrolled for the fall semester that begins in August, and including returning students. 

@DavidGeffen is among the most enterprising and influential figures in American entertainment and a philanthropist whose vigorous support advances health, education, arts and culture, and civil liberties, among other causes. 

Read more at news.yale.edu. Link in Stories. 

#yale
